methods.name: BeginTransaction
methods.description:
Starts a new transaction and returns a transactional object.
All reads/writes performed within a transaction will run with
serializable isolation.

methods.name: CommitTransaction
methods.description:
Commit transaction atomically commit all the changes
performed in the context of the transaction.
All the changes committed or none of them committed in
the case of error.

methods.name: RollbackTransaction
methods.description:
Rollback transaction discards all the changes
performed in the transaction

methods.name: Insert
methods.description:
Insert inserts new documents in the collection and returns a conflict if any of the document
passed in the batch already exists. Insert provides idempotency by rejecting request if document
already exists. To replace documents, REPLACE API should be used instead of INSERT.

methods.name: Replace
methods.description: Replace inserts the documents or replaces the existing documents in the collections.

methods.name: Delete
methods.description: Delete documents from the collection according to specified filter

methods.name: Update
methods.description:
Update range of documents in the collection according to
the specified filter and the fields projection

methods.name: Read
methods.description:
Read range of documents from the collection according to
 the specified filter

methods.name: CreateCollection
methods.description: Create new collection of documents in the specified database

methods.name: AlterCollection
methods.description: Change the schema of existing collection

methods.name: ListDatabases

methods.name: ListCollections

methods.name: CreateDatabase

methods.name: DropDatabase
methods.description:
Drop database deletes all the collections in the database
along with all it documents

Uses variable-length encoding. Signed int value. These more efficiently encode negative numbers than regular int32s.
Uses variable-length encoding. Signed int value. These more efficiently encode negative numbers than regular int64s.
Always four bytes. More efficient than uint32 if values are often greater than 2^28.
Always eight bytes. More efficient than uint64 if values are often greater than 2^56.
